N2  - Caliciviridae, including norovirus, are considered important sources of human gastroenteritis. As leafy green vegetables are commonly consumed without additional processing, it is important to evaluate interventions to reduce the presence of human pathogens in these products. Feline calicivirus was used as a model for small round structured viruses on lettuce. The lettuce was inoculated by immersion to simulate contamination from irrigation or wash water. The inoculated lettuce was then exposed to electron beam irradiation at various dose levels to determine survival. The D10-value of the calicivirus on lettuce was determined to be 2.95 kGy. Irradiation to reduce bacterial pathogens on cut lettuce could also reduce the risk associated with small round structured viruses on lettuce. Received 14 March 2011 Accepted 21 April 2011 From a food safety perspective, noroviruses, members of the family Caliciviridae, are responsible for widespread foodborne illnesses. They have been classified in the highest priority group of foodborne pathogens, and they are considered the most common foodborne virus (8). In the United States, it is estimated that there are more than 20 million cases of norovirus-associated foodborne illness every year (13). Produce including spinach and lettuce could become contaminated with norovirus either during growth, from contaminated water, or during processing and serving, by infected food handlers. Because these leafy green vegetables are often consumed without any further processing, it is prudent to investigate interventions that may lessen the chance of human infection by these foods. In 2008, the U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA) issued a final rule on the use of irradiation for spinach and lettuce, stating, “ . . . FDA concludes that the proposed use of irradiation to treat iceberg lettuce and spinach with absorbed doses that will not exceed 4.0 kGy is safe” (18). The final rule was in response to three multistate outbreaks of Escherichia coli O157:H7 traced to spinach and lettuce (3). Although the focus of this final rule was on bacterial contamination, it is possible that irradiation at the approved dose levels could potentially affect enteric virus populations as well. Several researchers have studied the inactivation of caliciviruses (a.k.a., small round structured viruses [SRSVs]) on surfaces and on foods. Slomka and Appleton (14) and Duizer et al. (7) demonstrated obvious time and temperature relationships in the inactivation of these viruses in molluscan shellfish and in water. Gulati et al. (9) evaluated the effectiveness of three commonly used disinfectants on strawberries and lettuce inoculated with feline calicivirus. Ozone (16), UV irradiation (17), and gamma irradiation (2) have also been shown to have various destructive effects on viruses in water or on food surfaces. All of these technologies have advantages and disadvantages from a processing perspective, and each could be of value in a specific processing operation or food service system. Since noroviruses are significant causes of human gastroenteritis, with very low infectious doses and do not readily grow in cell culture, researchers have looked for a similar virus to use as a surrogate for laboratory studies. Slomka and Appleton (14) suggested the use of feline calicivirus (FCV) as a surrogate for Norwalk virus in their research on heat inactivation of the virus in molluscan shellfish. Other researchers, including Doultree et al. (6), Gulati et al. (9), Mattison et al. (11), Thurston-Enriquez et al. 16., 17., and Duizer et al. (7), have also used FCV as a surrogate for SRSVs with foods and food surfaces. More recently, murine norovirus has been used as a surrogate for human norovirus on lettuce (1). However, from a research perspective, FCV appears to be an adequate surrogate for norovirus and other small, round structured human enteric viruses. Although gamma irradiation has been shown to be effective in reducing the populations of caliciviruses in foods, there is currently nothing in the scientific literature documenting the effects of electron beam irradiation. Although the results of the different irradiation sources would be assumed to be similar, electron beam irradiation has advantages from a processing perspective, in part because of a higher product throughput at a given dose. A disadvantage of electron beam irradiation, in comparison with gamma irradiation, is that electron beam irradiation has a relatively small depth of penetration. The objective of this study was to determine the relationship between electron beam irradiation and the inactivation of norovirus on leafy green vegetables, in the context of the approval of irradiation as a decontamination strategy for lettuce and spinach.
