ogramming was used to optimize the irrigation schedule at the subbasin scale. As a result, to satisfy the constraint of stopping groundwater drawdown, the average minimal reduction in the winter wheat yield would be 42% under the optimal irrigation schedule. By contrast, to satisfy the constraint of restricting the reduction in the crop yield to within the threshold required to maintain winter wheat self-sufficiency, the minimal rate of decline in the shallow groundwater table would be 0.26–0.52 m a−1 under the optimal irrigation schedule. In addition, the uncertainty in the simulated shallow groundwater variation in this study was acceptable, indicating that the above assessments could provide reasonable references for regional groundwater management.
